    ("LOC_CITY_NAME_FRANCE_GEDEMO_AIXLACHAPELLE",                                     "Aix-la-Chapelle"),
    ("LOC_TRAIT_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_NAME",                                     "Missi Dominici"),
    ("LOC_TRAIT_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_DESCRIPTION",                              "[ICON_DISTRICT_HOLYSITE] Holy Site district buildings provide [ICON_Gold] Gold equivalent to their [ICON_Faith] Faith output. Charlemagne can build the Paladin Unique Unit."),
    ("LOC_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1",                                                "Charlemagne"),
    ("LOC_LOADING_INFO_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1",                                   "O Great Charlemagne! You are the most famous sovereign of the Middle Ages. King of the Franks and emperor of the West, great conqueror and skillful administrator, he gave his name to a dynasty, that of the Carolingians. His empire was so vast that it appears in the history books of several countries of western Europe, including France and Germany.[NewLine]Can you build a civilization that will stand the test of time?"),
    ("LOC_PEDIA_LEADERS_PAGE_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_TITLE",                       "Charlemagne"),
    ("LOC_PEDIA_LEADERS_PAGE_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_SUBTITLE",                    "Holy Roman Emperor"),
    ("LOC_PEDIA_LEADERS_PAGE_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_QUOTE",                       "You count on your birth and you conceive of pride! Know that you will have no government or bishoprics if you are not more educated than others."),
    ("LOC_PEDIA_LEADERS_PAGE_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1",      "Charlemagne belongs to the Carolingian dynasty. Son of Pepin the Short, he is king of the Franks from 768, becomes by conquest king of the Lombards in 774 and is crowned emperor in Rome by Pope Leo III on 24 or 25 December 800, recognizing a dignity that has disappeared since the deposition of the last Roman emperor of the West in 476. King warrior, he significantly enlarged his kingdom by a series of military campaigns, especially against the pagan Saxons whose submission was difficult and violent, but also against the Lombards in Italy and the Muslims of al-Andalus. Sovereign reformer, concerned with religious orthodoxy and culture, he protects the arts and letters and is at the origin of the ""Carolingian renaissance"". His immediate political work, the Empire, did not survive him for long. In accordance with the Germanic custom of inheritance, Charlemagne foresees from 806 the division of the Empire between his three sons. After many adventures, the Empire will finally be divided in 843 between three of his grandsons, during the Treaty of Verdun. The feudal fragmentation of the following centuries and the formation in Europe of the rival nation-states condemn to impotence those who explicitly attempt to restore the universal empire of Charlemagne, especially the rulers of the Holy Roman Empire, Otto I in 962 to Charles V in the sixteenth century, even Napoleon I, haunted by the example of the most eminent Carolingians."),
    ("LOC_PEDIA_LEADERS_PAGE_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2",      "The figure of Charlemagne was the subject of rifts in Europe, including political issues between the twelfth and nineteenth century between the Germanic nation that considers the Holy Roman Empire as the legitimate successor of the Carolingian emperor and the French nation which makes it a central element of the dynastic continuity of the Capetians. He is sometimes considered the ""Father of Europe"" for bringing together a significant part of Western Europe, and laying down principles of government inherited from the great European states. The two main texts of the ninth century depicting the real Charlemagne, the Vita Caroli d'Enginhard and the Gesta Karoli Magni attributed to the monk of St. Gall Notker the Stammerer, the halo also legends and myths taken over the following centuries : ""There is the Charlemagne of the vassal and feudal society, the Charlemagne of the Crusade and the Reconquest, the Charlemagne inventor of the Crown of France or the Imperial Crown, the Charlemagne badly canonized but considered true saint of the Church, the Charlemagne of the good schoolchildren. ""Charlemagne is, by tolerance of Pope Benedict XIV, a blessed Catholic celebrated locally on January 28. In fact, in 1165, the Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa obtains the canonization of Charlemagne by the Antipope Pascal III Many dioceses in the North of France then inscribed Charlemagne on their calendar and in 1661 the University of Paris chose him as patron saint. the city of Aix-la-Chapelle venerates his relics. Yet the Catholic Church has removed from its calendar ""the emperor who converts the Saxons by the sword rather than by the peaceful preaching of the Gospel"""),
    ("LOC_DIPLO_FIRST_MEET_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_ANY",                           "Glory to you, friend! I am Charlemagne, Emperor of the Romans and stalwart defender of the Holy Kingdom of God. What light has beckoned you to me this day?"),
    ("LOC_DIPLO_FIRST_MEET_VISIT_RECIPIENT_LEADER_GEDEMO_CHARLEMAGNE1_ANY",           "Salutations, leader. I am Charlemagne, holy Emperor of the Romans and King of the Franks. Are you a pious ruler, as am I? Or at least, one worthy of my audience?"),
